---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Article from "../../components/Article.astro";
---

<Layout title="memento mori">
  <Article
    title="memento mori"
    section="death"
    updated="archive draft"
  >
    <p>
      memento mori means "remember that you will die." it is not meant to be
      morbid, but clarifying.
    </p>

    <p>
      to remember death is to remove illusion. it cuts through distraction,
      vanity, and false urgency, revealing what actually matters.
    </p>

    <p>
      this reminder has appeared across history—in philosophy, religion, art,
      and daily practice—not as fear, but as orientation.
    </p>

    <h2>clarity</h2>

    <p>
      when death is kept in mind, choices sharpen. time is no longer assumed to
      be endless, and meaning becomes more immediate.
    </p>

    <p>
      what once felt important may lose its weight. what was ignored may become
      central.
    </p>

    <h2>priority</h2>

    <p>
      memento mori reorganizes attention. it asks: what is worth doing, knowing
      that time is limited?
    </p>

    <p>
      this is not about urgency alone, but alignment. living in a way that is
      less divided and more real.
    </p>

    <h2>presence</h2>

    <p>
      remembering death can bring a deeper presence to life. moments are no
      longer treated as disposable.
    </p>

    <p>
      what is here becomes more vivid because it is known to pass.
    </p>

    <div class="mini-links">
      <a class="link-blue" href="/death">back to death index</a>
      <a class="link-blue" href="/death/rebirth">continue to: death + rebirth</a>
      <a class="link-red" href="/death/afterlife">afterlife</a>
    </div>
  </Article>
</Layout>
